abstract: SEATTLE — Thousands of miles of fiber-optic cables are strung across the world's oceans, connecting continents like so many tin cans in this age of critical global communication. So the fact that about 800 more miles of fiber-optic cable will soon thread the sea floor off the coast of the U.S. Pacific Northwest might not seem particularly revolutionary. Until you meet John Delaney, part oceanographer, part oracle.
